# CSRF where token is tied to non-session cookie

## Vulnerability Type
CSRF	

## Difficulty
practitioner

## Platform
PortSwigger Web Security Academy

## Goal
This lab's email change functionality is vulnerable to CSRF. It uses tokens to try to prevent CSRF attacks, but they aren't integrated into the site's session handling system

## Root Cause
This lab's email change functionality is vulnerable to CSRF because the CSRF token is tied to a non-session cookie that can be controlled by the attacker.

## Exploitation Steps
1. Browse the application  
2. login with provided credentials  
3. intercept email change request  
4. go to another account in private tab and note CSRF token and csrfKey cookie  
5. generate CSRF PoC and remove auto-submit  
6. inject csrfKey cookie into victim session  
7. submit request using attacker-controlled CSRF token and cookie pair  
8. exploit successful  

## Impact
An attacker can change user email address  

## What I Learned
in this lab i learned how CSRF protection can be bypassed when the token is tied to a non-session cookie  
